{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "Q28 is the hardest question in the module at 38% correct. The key inference depends on a single phrase ('simply adding') and its implications for existing exemptions. This question rewards close reading of proposal language.", "variant": "comment" }

 [After the breakdown block]

{{+add+}} Add a "Why This Is Hard" callout:
{{+**Why This Is Hard:** The key phrase is "simply adding." If the experts proposed radically overhauling the law, we could not predict which exemptions would survive. But because they propose a simple addition to existing law, we can infer that all existing provisions -- including the academic exemptions for "private study or research" -- would remain. Answer (E) at 30% is the main trap: it sounds reasonable but attributes a specific position on secondary copies to the experts, which the passage only raises as an open question, never as the experts' stated view.+}}

 [After the "Why This Is Hard" callout, at end of content array]

{{+add+}} Optional module wrap-up:
{{+**Module Takeaways:** This passage tested five questions across five distinct question types. Two key skills emerged: (1) Distinguishing between settled conclusions and open questions. The passage raises several unresolved issues (scope of the crime, enforceability, secondary copies), and the hardest questions (Q27, Q28) tested whether students could tell what the passage concludes from what it merely asks. (2) Reading proposal language carefully. The word "simply" in the experts' proposal was the key to Q28 -- it implied that existing law (including exemptions) would remain intact.+}}

